rComments: Love this man. SAS programming is confusing but there is plenty of opportunity in and out of lecture to make sure you understand the process and Corey is your number one fan. Hilarious and relatable in class and over email. As much a friend as he is an awesome prof.

Dr. Corey is by far the best professor I had at UofT. I had the honor to attend his statistical simulation seminar. Very enthusiastic professor. His lectures are the best and he makes sure every student understands all the SAS programs.

LIBNAME NO 'T:/'; DATA MAKE; SET NO.EXCUSES; COMMENT = 'Be warned: you must work smart. Here, you will learn what it means to be in Vic One. If you can't figure out some code by experimentation, or see through mistakes in course documents, it's about time you toughened up. Expect no more to be taught; expect to learn, discover, and survive.' RUN;

Friendly person. Poorly organized course. Poor lecture notes, made concepts more convoluted than necessary, full of formulas with no explanations. Poor didactic skills, but enthusiastic. Probably good that this course will be online only in the future.

Assignments contained detailed questions about untaught material; Getting the assignments done required googling of key terms; No text book was required but I think the course would have been more organised if we had a text book; Lecture notes were formula-based with minimal explanation and very often had errors;
prof corey was very attentive to students questions and accomodating...he also had a decent marking scheme designed to help his students and was enthusiastic about the world of statistics
Arrogant, unhelpful, far too busy to put any thought or work into what occurs in his classroom. Avoid at all costs.
